# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] The forces that cause adhesion and cohesion can be divided into several types.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] The intermolecular forces responsible for the function of various kinds of stickers and sticky tape fall into the categories of chemical adhesion, dispersive adhesion, and diffusive adhesion.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] In addition to the cumulative magnitudes of these intermolecular forces, there are also certain emergent mechanical effects.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Surface energy is conventionally defined as the work that is required to build an area of a particular surface.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Another way to view the surface energy is to relate it to the work required to cleave a bulk sample, creating two surfaces.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] If the new surfaces are identical, the surface energy γ of each surface is equal to half the work of cleavage, W: γ = (1/2)W11.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] If the surfaces are unequal, the Young-Dupré equation applies: W12 = γ1 + γ2 – γ12, where γ1 and γ2 are the surface energies of the two new surfaces, and γ12 is the interfacial energy.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] This methodology can also be used to discuss cleavage that happens in another medium: γ12 = (1/2)W121 = (1/2)W212.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] These two energy quantities refer to the energy that is needed to cleave one species into two pieces while it is contained in a medium of the other species.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Likewise for a three species system: γ13 + γ23 – γ12 = W12 + W33 – W13 – W23 = W132, where W132 is the energy of cleaving species 1 from species 2 in a medium of species 3.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] There is no single theory covering adhesion, and particular mechanisms are specific to particular material scenarios.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Adhesive materials fill the voids or pores of the surfaces and hold surfaces together by interlocking.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Other interlocking phenomena are observed on different length scales.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Sewing is an example of two materials forming a large scale mechanical bond, velcro forms one on a medium scale, and some textile adhesives (glue) form one at a small scale.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Two materials may form a compound at the joint.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] The strongest joints are where atoms of the two materials share or swap electrons (known respectively as covalent bonding or ionic bonding).
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] A weaker bond is formed if a hydrogen atom in one molecule is attracted to an atom of nitrogen, oxygen, or fluorine in another molecule, a phenomenon called hydrogen bonding.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Chemical adhesion occurs when the surface atoms of two separate surfaces form ionic, covalent, or hydrogen bonds.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] The engineering principle behind chemical adhesion in this sense is fairly straightforward: if surface molecules can bond, then the surfaces will be bonded together by a network of these bonds.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] It bears mentioning that these attractive ionic and covalent forces are effective over only very small distances – less than a nanometer.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] This means in general not only that surfaces with the potential for chemical bonding need to be brought very close together, but also that these bonds are fairly brittle, since the surfaces then need to be kept close together.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] In dispersive adhesion, also known as physisorption, two materials are held together by van der Waals forces: the attraction between two molecules, each of which has a region of slight positive and negative charge.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] In the simple case, such molecules are therefore polar with respect to average charge density, although in larger or more complex molecules, there may be multiple "poles" or regions of greater positive or negative charge.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] These positive and negative poles may be a permanent property of a molecule (Keesom forces) or a transient effect which can occur in any molecule, as the random movement of electrons within the molecules may result in a temporary concentration of electrons in one region (London forces).
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] In surface science, the term *adhesion* almost always refers to dispersive adhesion.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] In a typical solid-liquid-gas system (such as a drop of liquid on a solid surrounded by air) the contact angle is used to evaluate adhesiveness indirectly, while a Centrifugal Adhesion Balance allows for direct quantitative adhesion measurements.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Generally, cases where the contact angle is low are considered of higher adhesion per unit area.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] This approach assumes that the lower contact angle corresponds to a higher surface energy.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Theoretically, the more exact relation between contact angle and work of adhesion is more involved and is given by the Young-Dupre equation.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] The contact angle of the three-phase system is a function not only of dispersive adhesion (interaction between the molecules in the liquid and the molecules in the solid) but also cohesion (interaction between the liquid molecules themselves).
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Strong adhesion and weak cohesion results in a high degree of wetting, a lyophilic condition with low measured contact angles.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Conversely, weak adhesion and strong cohesion results in lyophobic conditions with high measured contact angles and poor wetting.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] London dispersion forces are particularly useful for the function of adhesive devices, because they do not require either surface to have any permanent polarity.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] They were described in the 1930s by Fritz London, and have been observed by many researchers.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Dispersive forces are a consequence of statistical quantum mechanics.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] London theorized that attractive forces between molecules that cannot be explained by ionic or covalent interaction can be caused by polar moments within molecules.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Multipoles could account for attraction between molecules having permanent multipole moments that participate in electrostatic interaction.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] However, experimental data showed that many of the compounds observed to experience van der Waals forces had no multipoles at all.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] London suggested that momentary dipoles are induced purely by virtue of molecules being in proximity to one another.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] While the first term is simply the zero-point energy, the negative second term describes an attractive force between neighboring oscillators.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] The same argument can also be extended to a large number of coupled oscillators, and thus skirts issues that would negate the large scale attractive effects of permanent dipoles cancelling through symmetry, in particular.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] The additive nature of the dispersion effect has another useful consequence.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Consider a single such dispersive dipole, referred to as the origin dipole.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] When considering identical particles, this is called cohesive force.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] When discussing adhesion, this theory needs to be converted into terms relating to surfaces.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] If there is a net attractive energy of cohesion in a bulk of similar molecules, then cleaving this bulk to produce two surfaces will yield surfaces with a dispersive surface energy, since the form of the energy remain the same.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] This theory provides a basis for the existence of van der Waals forces at the surface, which exist between any molecules having electrons.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] These forces are easily observed through the spontaneous jumping of smooth surfaces into contact.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Smooth surfaces of mica, gold, various polymers and solid gelatin solutions do not stay apart when their separating becomes small enough – on the order of 1–10 nm.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] where P is the force (negative for attraction), z is the separation distance, and A is a material-specific constant called the Hamaker constant.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] The effect is also apparent in experiments where a polydimethylsiloxane (PDMS) stamp is made with small periodic post structures.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] The surface with the posts is placed face down on a smooth surface, such that the surface area in between each post is elevated above the smooth surface, like a roof supported by columns.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Because of these attractive dispersive forces between the PDMS and the smooth substrate, the elevated surface – or "roof" – collapses down onto the substrate without any external force aside from the van der Waals attraction.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Simple smooth polymer surfaces – without any microstructures – are commonly used for these dispersive adhesive properties.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Decals and stickers that adhere to glass without using any chemical adhesives are fairly common as toys and decorations and useful as removable labels because they do not rapidly lose their adhesive properties, as do sticky tapes that use adhesive chemical compounds.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] These forces also act over very small distances – 99% of the work necessary to break van der Waals bonds is done once surfaces are pulled more than a nanometer apart.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] As a result of this limited motion in both the van der Waals and ionic/covalent bonding situations, practical effectiveness of adhesion due to either or both of these interactions leaves much to be desired.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Once a crack is initiated, it propagates easily along the interface because of the brittle nature of the interfacial bonds.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] As an additional consequence, increasing surface area often does little to enhance the strength of the adhesion in this situation.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] This follows from the aforementioned crack failure – the stress at the interface is not uniformly distributed, but rather concentrated at the area of failure.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Some conducting materials may pass electrons to form a difference in electrical charge at the joint.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] This results in a structure similar to a capacitor and creates an attractive electrostatic force between the materials.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Some materials may merge at the joint by diffusion.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] This may occur when the molecules of both materials are mobile and soluble in each other.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] This would be particularly effective with polymer chains where one end of the molecule diffuses into the other material.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] It is also the mechanism involved in sintering.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] When metal or ceramic powders are pressed together and heated, atoms diffuse from one particle to the next.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Diffusive forces are somewhat like mechanical tethering at the molecular level.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Diffusive bonding occurs when species from one surface penetrate into an adjacent surface while still being bound to the phase of their surface of origin.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] One instructive example is that of polymer-on-polymer surfaces.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Diffusive bonding in polymer-on-polymer surfaces is the result of sections of polymer chains from one surface interdigitating with those of an adjacent surface.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] The freedom of movement of the polymers has a strong effect on their ability to interdigitate, and hence, on diffusive bonding.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] For example, cross-linked polymers are less capable of diffusion and interdigitation because they are bonded together at many points of contact, and are not free to twist into the adjacent surface.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Uncrosslinked polymers (thermoplastics), on the other hand are freer to wander into the adjacent phase by extending tails and loops across the interface.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Another circumstance under which diffusive bonding occurs is "scission".
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Chain scission is the cutting up of polymer chains, resulting in a higher concentration of distal tails.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] The heightened concentration of these chain ends gives rise to a heightened concentration of polymer tails extending across the interface.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Scission is easily achieved by ultraviolet irradiation in the presence of oxygen gas, which suggests that adhesive devices employing diffusive bonding actually benefit from prolonged exposure to heat/light and air.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] The longer such a device is exposed to these conditions, the more tails are scissed and branch out across the interface.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Once across the interface, the tails and loops form whatever bonds are favorable.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] In the case of polymer-on-polymer surfaces, this means more van der Waals forces.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] While these may be brittle, they are quite strong when a large network of these bonds is formed.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] The outermost layer of each surface plays a crucial role in the adhesive properties of such interfaces, as even a tiny amount of interdigitation – as little as one or two tails of 1.25 angstrom length – can increase the van der Waals bonds by an order of magnitude.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] The strength of the adhesion between two materials depends on which of the above mechanisms occur between the two materials, and the surface area over which the two materials contact.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Materials that wet against each other tend to have a larger contact area than those that do not.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Wetting depends on the surface energy of the materials.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Low surface energy materials such as polyethylene, polypropylene, polytetrafluoroethylene and polyoxymethylene are difficult to bond without special surface preparation.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Another factor determining the strength of an adhesive contact is its shape.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Adhesive contacts of complex shape begin to detach at the "edges" of the contact area.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] The process of destruction of adhesive contacts can be seen in the film.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Recent experimental work has shown that adhesion-force measurements often exhibit non-Gaussian variability, and in some cases the normalized force distribution can be accurately represented using a Beta distribution.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] In concert with the primary surface forces described above, there are several circumstantial effects in play.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] While the forces themselves each contribute to the magnitude of the adhesion between the surfaces, the following play a crucial role in the overall strength and reliability of an adhesive device.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Stringing is perhaps the most crucial of these effects, and is often seen on adhesive tapes.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Stringing occurs when a separation of two surfaces is beginning and molecules at the interface bridge out across the gap, rather than cracking like the interface itself.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] The most significant consequence of this effect is the restraint of the crack.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] By providing the otherwise brittle interfacial bonds with some flexibility, the molecules that are stringing across the gap can stop the crack from propagating.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Another way to understand this phenomenon is by comparing it to the stress concentration at the point of failure mentioned earlier.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Since the stress is now spread out over some area, the stress at any given point has less of a chance of overwhelming the total adhesive force between the surfaces.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] If failure does occur at an interface containing a viscoelastic adhesive agent, and a crack does propagate, it happens by a gradual process called "fingering", rather than a rapid, brittle fracture.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Stringing can apply to both the diffusive bonding regime and the chemical bonding regime.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] The strings of molecules bridging across the gap would either be the molecules that had earlier diffused across the interface or the viscoelastic adhesive, provided that there was a significant volume of it at the interface.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] The interplay of molecular scale mechanisms and hierarchical surface structures is known to result in high levels of static friction and bonding between pairs of surfaces.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Technologically advanced adhesive devices sometimes make use of microstructures on surfaces, such as tightly packed periodic posts.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] These are biomimetic technologies inspired by the adhesive abilities of the feet of various arthropods and vertebrates (most notably, geckos).
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] By intermixing periodic breaks into smooth, adhesive surfaces, the interface acquires valuable crack-arresting properties.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Because crack initiation requires much greater stress than does crack propagation, surfaces like these are much harder to separate, as a new crack has to be restarted every time the next individual microstructure is reached.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Hysteresis, in this case, refers to the restructuring of the adhesive interface over some period of time, with the result being that the work needed to separate two surfaces is greater than the work that was gained by bringing them together (W > γ1 + γ2).
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] For the most part, this is a phenomenon associated with diffusive bonding.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] The more time is given for a pair of surfaces exhibiting diffusive bonding to restructure, the more diffusion will occur, the stronger the adhesion will become.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] The aforementioned reaction of certain polymer-on-polymer surfaces to ultraviolet radiation and oxygen gas is an instance of hysteresis, but it will also happen over time without those factors.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] In addition to being able to observe hysteresis by determining if W > γ1 + γ2 is true, one can also find evidence of it by performing "stop-start" measurements.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] In these experiments, two surfaces slide against one another continuously and occasionally stopped for some measured amount of time.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Results from experiments on polymer-on-polymer surfaces show that if the stopping time is short enough, resumption of smooth sliding is easy.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] If, however, the stopping time exceeds some limit, there is an initial increase of resistance to motion, indicating that the stopping time was sufficient for the surfaces to restructure.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Some atmospheric effects on the functionality of adhesive devices can be characterized by following the theory of surface energy and interfacial tension.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] If γ12 is high, then each species finds it favorable to cohere while in contact with a foreign species, rather than dissociate and mix with the other.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] If this is true, then it follows that when the interfacial tension is high, the force of adhesion is weak, since each species does not find it favorable to bond to the other.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] The interfacial tension of a liquid and a solid is directly related to the liquid's wettability (relative to the solid), and thus one can extrapolate that cohesion increases in non-wetting liquids and decreases in wetting liquids.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] One example that verifies this is polydimethyl siloxane rubber, which has a work of self-adhesion of 43.6 mJ/m2 in air, 74 mJ/m2 in water (a nonwetting liquid) and 6 mJ/m2 in methanol (a wetting liquid).
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] This argument can be extended to the idea that when a surface is in a medium with which binding is favorable, it will be less likely to adhere to another surface, since the medium is taking up the potential sites on the surface that would otherwise be available to adhere to another surface.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Naturally this applies very strongly to wetting liquids, but also to gas molecules that could adsorb onto the surface in question, thereby occupying potential adhesion sites.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] This last point is actually fairly intuitive: Leaving an adhesive exposed to air too long gets it dirty, and its adhesive strength will decrease.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] This is observed in the experiment: when mica is cleaved in air, its cleavage energy, W121 or Wmica/air/mica, is smaller than the cleavage energy in vacuum, Wmica/vac/mica, by a factor of 13.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Lateral adhesion is associated with sliding one object on a substrate, such as sliding a drop on a surface.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] When the two objects are solids, either with or without a liquid between them, the lateral adhesion is described as *friction*.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] However, the behavior of lateral adhesion between a drop and a surface is tribologically very different from friction between solids, and the naturally adhesive contact between a flat surface and a liquid drop makes the lateral adhesion in this case, an individual field.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adhesion] Lateral adhesion can be measured using the centrifugal adhesion balance (CAB), which uses a combination of centrifugal and gravitational forces to decouple the normal and lateral forces in the problem.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adolf-eugen-fick] Fick began his work in the formal study of mathematics and physics before realising an aptitude for medicine.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adolf-eugen-fick] He then earned his doctorate in medicine from the University of Marburg in 1851.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adolf-eugen-fick] As a fresh medical graduate, he began his work as a prosector.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adolf-eugen-fick] In 1855, he introduced Fick's laws of diffusion, which govern the diffusion of a gas across a fluid membrane.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adolf-eugen-fick] In 1870, he was the first to measure cardiac output, using what is now called the Fick principle.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adolf-eugen-fick] Fick managed to double-publish his law of diffusion, as it applied equally to physiology and physics.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adolf-eugen-fick] His work led to the development of the direct Fick method for measuring cardiac output.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/adolf-eugen-fick] Fick's nephew, Adolf Gaston Eugen Fick, invented the contact lens.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] In *On Floating Bodies*, Archimedes suggested that (c.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Archimedes' principle allows the buoyancy of any floating object partially or fully immersed in a fluid to be calculated.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] The downward force on the object is simply its weight.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] The upward, or buoyant, force on the object is that stated by Archimedes' principle above.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Thus, the net force on the object is the difference between the magnitudes of the buoyant force and its weight.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] If this net force is positive, the object rises; if negative, the object sinks; and if zero, the object is neutrally buoyant—that is, it remains in place without either rising or sinking.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] In simple words, Archimedes' principle states that, when a body is partially or completely immersed in a fluid, it experiences an apparent loss in weight that is equal to the weight of the fluid displaced by the immersed part of the body(s).
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Consider a cuboid immersed in a fluid, its top and bottom faces orthogonal to the direction of gravity (assumed constant across the cube's stretch).
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] The fluid will exert a normal force on each face, but only the normal forces on top and bottom will contribute to buoyancy.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] The pressure difference between the bottom and the top face is directly proportional to the height (difference in depth of submersion).
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Multiplying the pressure difference by the area of a face gives a net force on the cuboid—the buoyancy—equaling in magnitude the weight of the fluid displaced by the cuboid.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] By summing up sufficiently many arbitrarily small cuboids this reasoning may be extended to irregular shapes, and so, whatever the shape of the submerged body, the buoyant force is equal to the weight of the displaced fluid.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] The weight of the displaced fluid is directly proportional to the volume of the displaced fluid (if the surrounding fluid is of uniform density).
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] The apparent weight of the object in the fluid is reduced, because of the force acting on it, which is called upthrust.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] where $F_{a}$ denotes the buoyant force applied onto the submerged object, $\rho$ denotes the density of the fluid, V represents the volume of the displaced fluid and g is the acceleration due to gravity.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Thus, among completely submerged objects with equal masses, objects with greater volume have greater buoyancy.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Suppose a rock's weight is measured as 10 newtons when suspended by a string in a vacuum with gravity acting on it.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Suppose that, when the rock is lowered into the water, it displaces water of weight 3 newtons.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] The force it then exerts on the string from which it hangs would be 10 newtons minus the 3 newtons of buoyant force: 10 − 3 = 7 newtons.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Buoyancy reduces the apparent weight of an object.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] It is generally easier to lift an object through the water than it is to pull it out of the water.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Example: If you drop wood into water, buoyancy will keep it afloat.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Example: A helium balloon in a moving car.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] When increasing speed or driving in a curve, the air moves in the opposite direction to the car's acceleration.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] However, due to buoyancy, the balloon is pushed "out of the way" by the air and will drift in the same direction as the car's acceleration.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] When an object is immersed in a liquid, the liquid exerts an upward force, which is known as the buoyant force, that is proportional to the weight of the displaced liquid.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Consequently, the net force acting on the object is equal to the difference between the weight of the object, or 'down' force, and the weight of the displaced fluid, or 'up' force.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Equilibrium, or neutral buoyancy, is achieved when these two weights and thus forces are equal.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] where **f** is the force density exerted by some outer field on the fluid, and *σ* is the Cauchy stress tensor.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Therefore, the shape of the open surface of a fluid equals the equipotential plane of the applied outer conservative force field.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] In this case the field is gravity, so Φ = −*ρfgz* where *g* is the gravitational acceleration, *ρf* is the mass density of the fluid.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] So pressure increases with depth below the surface of a liquid, as *z* denotes the distance from the surface of the liquid into it.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Any object with a non-zero vertical depth will have different pressures on its top and bottom, with the pressure on the bottom being greater.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] This difference in pressure causes the upward buoyancy force.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] The buoyancy force exerted on a body can now be calculated easily, since the internal pressure of the fluid is known.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] where *V* is the measure of the volume in contact with the fluid, that is the volume of the submerged part of the body, since the fluid doesn't exert force on the part of the body which is outside of it.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] The magnitude of buoyancy force may be appreciated a bit more from the following argument.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Consider any object of arbitrary shape and volume *V* surrounded by a liquid.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] The force the liquid exerts on an object within the liquid is equal to the weight of the liquid with a volume equal to that of the object.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] where *ρf* is the density of the fluid, *Vdisp* is the volume of the displaced body of liquid, and *g* is the gravitational acceleration at the location in question.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] If this volume of liquid is replaced by a solid body of exactly the same shape, the force the liquid exerts on it must be exactly the same as above.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] If the buoyancy of an (unrestrained and unpowered) object exceeds its weight, it tends to rise.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] An object whose weight exceeds its buoyancy tends to sink.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Calculation of the upwards force on a submerged object during its accelerating period cannot be done by the Archimedes principle alone; it is necessary to consider dynamics of an object involving buoyancy.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Once it fully sinks to the floor of the fluid or rises to the surface and settles, Archimedes principle can be applied alone.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] For a floating object, only the submerged volume displaces water.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] For a sunken object, the entire volume displaces water, and there will be an additional force of reaction from the solid floor.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] showing that the depth to which a floating object will sink, and the volume of fluid it will displace, is independent of the gravitational field regardless of geographic location.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] It can be the case that forces other than just buoyancy and gravity come into play.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] This is the case if the object is restrained or if the object sinks to the solid floor.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] An object which tends to float requires a tension restraint force T in order to remain fully submerged.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] An object which tends to sink will eventually have a normal force of constraint N exerted upon it by the solid floor.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] The constraint force can be tension in a spring scale measuring its weight in the fluid, and is how apparent weight is defined.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Another possible formula for calculating buoyancy of an object is by finding the apparent weight of that particular object in the air (calculated in Newtons), and apparent weight of that object in the water (in Newtons).
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] The final result would be measured in Newtons.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Air's density is very small compared to most solids and liquids.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] For this reason, the weight of an object in air is approximately the same as its true weight in a vacuum.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] The buoyancy of air is neglected for most objects during a measurement in air because the error is usually insignificant (typically less than 0.1% except for objects of very low average density such as a balloon or light foam).
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Consider a cube immersed in a fluid with the upper surface horizontal.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] The sides are identical in area, and have the same depth distribution, therefore they also have the same pressure distribution, and consequently the same total force resulting from hydrostatic pressure, exerted perpendicular to the plane of the surface of each side.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] There are two pairs of opposing sides, therefore the resultant horizontal forces balance in both orthogonal directions, and the resultant force is zero.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] The upward force on the cube is the pressure on the bottom surface integrated over its area.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] The surface is at constant depth, so the pressure is constant.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Therefore, the integral of the pressure over the area of the horizontal bottom surface of the cube is the hydrostatic pressure at that depth multiplied by the area of the bottom surface.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Similarly, the downward force on the cube is the pressure on the top surface integrated over its area.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Therefore, the integral of the pressure over the area of the horizontal top surface of the cube is the hydrostatic pressure at that depth multiplied by the area of the top surface.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] This means that the resultant upward force on the cube is equal to the weight of the fluid that would fit into the volume of the cube, and the downward force on the cube is its weight, in the absence of external forces.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] This analogy is valid for variations in the size of the cube.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] This analogy can be extended to an arbitrary number of cubes.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] An object of any shape can be approximated as a group of cubes in contact with each other, and as the size of the cubes is decreased, the precision of the approximation increases.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] The limiting case for infinitely small cubes is the exact equivalence.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Angled surfaces do not nullify the analogy as the resultant force can be split into orthogonal components and each dealt with in the same way.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Archimedes' principle does not consider the surface tension (capillarity) acting on the body.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Moreover, Archimedes' principle has been found to break down in complex fluids.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] There is an exception to Archimedes' principle known as the bottom (or side) case.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] This occurs when a side of the object is touching the bottom (or side) of the vessel it is submerged in, and no liquid seeps in along that side.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] In this case, the net force has been found to be different from Archimedes' principle, as, since no fluid seeps in on that side, the symmetry of pressure is broken.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Archimedes' principle shows the buoyant force and displacement of fluid.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] However, the concept of Archimedes' principle can be applied when considering why objects float.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] In other words, for an object floating on a liquid surface (like a boat) or floating submerged in a fluid (like a submarine in water or dirigible in air) the weight of the displaced fluid equals the weight of the object.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Thus, only in the special case of floating does the buoyant force acting on an object equal the objects weight.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] As iron is nearly eight times as dense as water, it displaces only 1/8 ton of water when submerged, which is not enough to keep it afloat.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Suppose the same iron block is reshaped into a bowl.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] It still weighs 1 ton, but when it is put in water, it displaces a greater volume of water than when it was a block.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] The deeper the iron bowl is immersed, the more water it displaces, and the greater the buoyant force acting on it.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] When the buoyant force equals 1 ton, it will sink no farther.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] When any boat displaces a weight of water equal to its own weight, it floats.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] This is often called the "principle of flotation": A floating object displaces a weight of fluid equal to its own weight.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Every ship, submarine, and dirigible must be designed to displace a weight of fluid at least equal to its own weight.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] A 10,000-ton ship's hull must be built wide enough, long enough and deep enough to displace 10,000 tons of water and still have some hull above the water to prevent it from sinking.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] It needs extra hull to fight waves that would otherwise fill it and, by increasing its mass, cause it to submerge.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] The same is true for vessels in air: a dirigible that weighs 100 tons needs to displace 100 tons of air.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] If it displaces more, it rises; if it displaces less, it falls.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] If the dirigible displaces exactly its weight, it hovers at a constant altitude.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] While they are related to it, the principle of flotation and the concept that a submerged object displaces a volume of fluid equal to its own volume are *not* Archimedes' principle.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Archimedes' principle, as stated above, equates the *buoyant force* to the weight of the fluid displaced.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] One common point of confusion regarding Archimedes' principle is the meaning of displaced volume.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Common demonstrations involve measuring the rise in water level when an object floats on the surface in order to calculate the displaced water.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] This measurement approach fails with a buoyant submerged object because the rise in the water level is directly related to the volume of the object and not the mass (except if the effective density of the object equals exactly the fluid density).
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] Archimedes reportedly exclaimed "Eureka" after he realized how to detect whether a crown is made of impure gold.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] While he did not use Archimedes' principle in the widespread tale and used displaced water only for measuring the volume of the crown, there is an alternative approach using the principle: Balance the crown and pure gold on a scale in the air and then put the scale into water.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/archimedes-principle] According to Archimedes' principle, if the density of the crown differs from the density of pure gold, the scale will get out of balance under water.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] An **atmosphere** is a layer of gases that envelop an astronomical object, held in place by the gravity of the object.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The name originates from Ancient Greek ἀτμός*(*atmós*)* 'vapour, steam' and σφαῖρα*(*sphaîra*)* 'sphere'.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] An object acquires most of its atmosphere during its primordial epoch, either by accretion of matter or by outgassing of volatiles.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The chemical interaction of the atmosphere with the solid surface can change its fundamental composition, as can photochemical interaction with the Sun.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] A planet retains an atmosphere for longer durations when the gravity is high and the temperature is low.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The solar wind works to strip away a planet's outer atmosphere, although this process is slowed by a magnetosphere.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The further a body is from the Sun, the lower the rate of atmospheric stripping.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Aside from Mercury, all Solar System planets have substantial atmospheres, as does the dwarf planet Pluto and the moon Titan.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The high gravity and low temperature of Jupiter and the other gas giant planets allow them to retain massive atmospheres of mostly hydrogen and helium.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Lower mass terrestrial planets orbit closer to the Sun, and so mainly retain higher molar mass atmospheres made of carbon, nitrogen, and oxygen, with trace amounts of inert gas.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Atmospheres have been detected around exoplanets such as HD 209458 b and Kepler-7b.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] A stellar atmosphere is the outer region of a star, which includes the layers above the opaque photosphere; stars of low temperature might have outer atmospheres containing compound molecules.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Other objects with atmospheres are brown dwarfs and active comets.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] In the nebular hypothesis, stars form during the gravitational collapse of a mass of gas and dust within an interstellar molecular cloud.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] This material forms a pancake-like rotating disk with the mass concentrated at the center.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The protostar is created at the central mass concentration, while the planets and satellites are formed in the disk through a process of accretion.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Dust settles into the median disk plane, forming materials that can collide and accrete to create planetesimals.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Close to the star, these bodies grow and accumulate to form protoplanets consisting primarily of refractory materials with few volatiles.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Further from the star, planetary embryos are created from accumulation of volatiles up to around ten times the mass of the Earth or more.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Masses of gas are then acquired from the surrounding disk nebula, forming a gas giant around the embryo.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Planetary satellites form in a similar fashion from the disk of material around the planets.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The primary atmosphere of a planet is produced when the gravity is sufficient to retain accreted gas against escape processes.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The latter can include collisions with other bodies that impart sufficient energy for the gasses to escape.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] For the terrestrial planets, the high temperatures generated by their initial bombardment results in the outgassing of volatiles, creating the secondary atmosphere.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The original composition and thickness of the atmosphere is thus determined by the stellar nebula's chemistry and temperature, but can be modified by processes within the astronomical body that release different atmospheric components.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The circumstellar disk will finally dissipate on time scales of about 107 years, and the star will complete its contraction then ignite hydrogen fusion at its core in a time frame determined by its mass.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The atmospheres of the planets Venus and Mars are principally composed of carbon dioxide, nitrogen, and argon.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Because Venus has no oceans or rain to dissolve the carbon dioxide, large amounts of this greenhouse gas has remained in the atmosphere.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The result is a dense atmosphere about 80 times the pressure of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The planet's lack of a magnetic field and closer proximity to the Sun resulted in the loss of its hydrogen (in the form of water) after two billion years.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Because Mars is small, cold, and lacks a magnetic field, it has retained only a sparse atmosphere.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The surface air pressure of 0.6 kPa for Mars is only 0.6% of Earth's 101.3 kPa.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The planet has probably lost at least 80–85% of its original water supply to space.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] However, the planet has retained significant deposits of frozen water and carbon dioxide.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] If all of the frozen CO2 were to sublimate, the air pressure could climb to 30 kPa.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] This is comparable to the air pressure on the top of Mount Everest.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The composition of Earth's atmosphere is determined by the by-products of the life that it sustains.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Dry air (mixture of gases) from Earth's atmosphere contains 78.08% nitrogen, 20.95% oxygen, 0.93% argon, 0.04% carbon dioxide, and traces of hydrogen, helium, and other "noble" gases (by volume), but generally a variable amount of water vapor is also present, on average about 1% at sea level.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Earth's persistent magnetosphere acts as a shield against atmospheric scavenging by the solar wind, as it fends off the incoming plasma at a distance of about 10 Earth radii.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The low temperatures and higher escape velocities of the Solar System's giant planets—Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus and Neptune—allow them more readily to retain gases with low molecular masses.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] These planets have reducing atmospheres of hydrogen and helium, with trace amounts of other elements and more complex compounds.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Unlike the terrestrial planets, the gas giants lack a well-defined surface.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Instead the atmosphere is maintained in hydrostatic equilibrium by intense pressure deep in the body.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The dynamic weather on these bodies only occurs in a relatively thin surface layer.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Two satellites of the outer planets possess significant atmospheres.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Titan, a moon of Saturn, and Triton, a moon of Neptune, have atmospheres mainly of nitrogen.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] When in the part of its orbit closest to the Sun, Pluto has an atmosphere of nitrogen and methane similar to Triton's, but these gases are frozen when it is farther from the Sun.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Other bodies within the Solar System have extremely thin atmospheres not in equilibrium.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] These include the Moon (sodium gas, noble gases, hydrogen), Mercury (sodium gas), Callisto (carbon dioxide and oxygen), Europa (oxygen), Io (sulfur dioxide), and Enceladus (water vapor).
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Planetary objects around distant stars, known as exoplanets, span a more diverse range of physical properties than is found in the Solar System.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] These targets provide an opportunity to study atmospheres around a broad span of objects and conditions.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] However, observations of these targets requires much more sensitive instrumentation.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The methods used to analyze these remote atmospheres are transit spectroscopy, high-resolution Doppler spectroscopy, and direct imaging.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Transit spectroscopy uses the transit of an exoplanet across its host star to detect its atmosphere.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] By comparing the radius at different wavelengths, the presence of specific components can be detected.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The first such detection was in 2002, when sodium was detected in the atmosphere of HD 209458b, a gas giant with a close orbit around a star in the constellation Pegasus.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Its atmosphere is heated to temperatures over 1,000 K, and is steadily escaping into space.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Hydrogen, oxygen, and carbon have been detected in the planet's inflated atmosphere by Hubble observations.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Since 2002, potassium has been detected in the atmosphere of XO-2Nb, and both sodium and potassium in HD 189733 b's atmosphere.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Many of the discovered super earths have orbits close enough to their host star that their surfaces are expected to be magma oceans.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The secondary atmospheres of these lava planets most likely consist of materials that have been vaporized from the magma, such as sodium, potassium, oxygen, and silicon oxide.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] An atmosphere in hydrostatic equilibrium consists of a balance between the air pressure created by the motions of the molecules, and the restraining force of gravity that prevents the molecules from escaping.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The pressure decreases in altitude, producing a pressure-gradient force.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Atmospheric pressure is the force (per unit-area) perpendicular to a unit-area of planetary surface, as determined by the weight of the vertical column of atmospheric gases.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] In said atmospheric model, the atmospheric pressure, the weight of the mass of the gas, decreases at high altitude because of the diminishing mass of the gas above the point of barometric measurement.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Air pressure varies by place and time due to meteorological conditions and atmospheric waves.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Units of air pressure are based upon the standard atmosphere (atm), which is 101,325 Pa (equivalent to 760 Torr or 14.696 psi).
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] For an ideal gas atmosphere, the height at which the atmospheric pressure declines by a factor of *e* (the base of the natural logarithm) is called the scale height (*H*).
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] For an atmosphere of uniform temperature, the scale height is proportional to the atmospheric temperature and is inversely proportional to the product of the mean molecular mass of dry air, and the local acceleration of gravity at the point of barometric measurement.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The temperature of the atmosphere is determined by an energy budget, which balances the heating from the incoming solar energy against the heat radiated back into space.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The incoming energy is determined by the distance from the Sun, and the energy reflected back out by the planetary albedo.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] When a planet is in radiative equilibrium, it has a planetary equilibrium temperature.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] This differs from the global mean temperature, which may be warmer than the equilibrium temperature due to the atmospheric greenhouse effect.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] For example, Venus has a surface temperature of almost 460 C compared to an equilibrium temperature of −40 C.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Planetary atmospheres are composed of layers with different properties, such as specific gaseous composition, temperature gradients, and pressure.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] For Earth, Mars, and Venus, the lowest level of the atmosphere is the troposphere, where most of the planet's clouds and weather are found.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] This extends from the ground up to 65 km on Venus, 40 km on Mars, and 17 km on Earth.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The troposphere contains the bulk of the atmosphere, possessing 80%–98% of the total atmospheric mass.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Temperature varies by altitude according to the lapse rate, as thermal energy from the ground is transported upward via convection.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Infrared radiation becomes trapped by molecules of gas and water vapor.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] For the Earth, the next layer is the stratosphere, which is a region of temperature increasing with altitude, creating a temperature inversion.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] This region contains the UV-absorbing ozone layer, at an altitude between 15 km and 35 km, which is responsible for the temperature rise.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Energy transport in this region occurs through radiation processes.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Lacking an oxygenated atmosphere to generate a significant layer of ozone, neither Mars nor Venus have a stratosphere.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Above the troposphere-stratosphere, the next layer of the atmosphere is termed the mesosphere.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] In this region, the water vapor and carbon dioxide serves as a heat sink that radiates energy in the infrared.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] As a result, the temperature of the mesosphere decreases with altitude, reaching the coldest layer of the atmosphere at the top.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Both Venus and Mars have an altitude range in the mesosphere where the temperature is nearly isothermal; for Mars this is above 120 km, while for Venus it is between 63 and 75 km altitude.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] In the lower regions of the atmosphere, turbulent mixing causes the atmospheric constituents to be evenly distributed.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Above a transition layer called the homopause, molecular diffusion dominates.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] This results in diffuse separation of the constituents by atomic weight; that is, lower mass components diffuse upward leaving higher mass molecules near the bottom.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The homopause is at an altitude of 100–110 km for the Earth, 115–130 km for Mars, and 135–150 km for Venus.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Beyond the mesosphere is a region of the atmosphere called the thermosphere that absorbs X-rays and extreme UV from the Sun, causing temperature to rise with altitude.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The thermal properties of this layer vary daily and with solar activity cycles.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The atmospheric region from the ground through the thermosphere is referred to as the barosphere, since the barometric law holds throughout.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The outermost layer of a planetary atmosphere is termed the exosphere.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Here, the air pressure is so low at this altitude that the distance travelled between molecule collisions, the mean free path, is greater than the atmospheric scale height.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] In this region, lower mass components with a thermal velocity exceeding the escape velocity can escape into space.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] For the Earth, the exosphere is at an altitude of 500 km, while it is around 210 km for Venus and Mars.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] On Earth, the exosphere extends to roughly 10,000 km, where it interacts with the magnetosphere of Earth.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] All three planets have an ionosphere, which is an ionized region of the upper atmosphere.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The ionospheres for Mars and Venus are closer to the surface and are less dense than on the Earth.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The density of the Earth's ionosphere is greater at short distances from the planetary surface in the daytime and decreases as the ionosphere rises at night-time, thereby allowing a greater range of radio frequencies to travel greater distances.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Gas giants are primarily composed of hydrogen and helium with traces of other elements, giving the planets a low bulk density.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Many of the molecules observed in the outer atmosphere are hydrides, and most of these (with the exception of H2O and H2S) are photochemically destroyed by solar UV in the stratosphere of Jupiter and Saturn.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] These compounds get re-created by thermo-chemical reactions within the hotter, lower regions of the atmosphere.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Complex organic compounds are recycled back to methane by the highly reducing atmosphere.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The high gravity of these planets combined with their distance from the Sun means that mass loss from their exospheres is negligible, so they form closed systems.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] A common feature of the gas giant planets are cloud layers that form where the combination of temperature and pressure are appropriate for condensing a particular volatile.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] For Jupiter and Saturn, the outermost cloud layer consists of ice particles of ammonia (NH3), with an underlying layer of ammonium hydrosulfide (NH4SH), then a deep layer of water clouds (H2O).
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] For Uranus and Neptune, the top layer is a methane (CH4) layer of ice particles, followed by the same cloud layers as Jupiter and Saturn.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] One difference for Uranus and Neptune is that hydrogen sulfide (H2S) mixes at the same level as the condensed ammonia.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] These cloud layers are optically thick, absorbing light at all wavelengths.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The result is a shallower scale height for the outer atmosphere.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] All four gas giants experience lightning activity in the water clouds, and this is generally much more powerful than terrestrial lightning.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Lightning has been observed on Jupiter, but has not been optically detected on Saturn, Uranus, or Neptune most likely because of their depth.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] All of the gas giants have internal heat sources and radiate more heat than they receive from the Sun.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Models for the interiors of Jupiter and Saturn suggest that at a certain depth the hydrogen undergoes a phase change to a metallic hydrogen fluid mixed with ice.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] There is possibly a diffuse or solid core of more massive elements.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] For Uranus and Neptune, there is no metallic hydrogen; instead there are interior layers of ice, placing these worlds in the sub-category of ice giants.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] At sufficient depth, the ice may transition to a supercritical fluid.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Within the Solar System, gas giant planets formed beyond the frost line, where the temperature from the young Sun was low enough for volatiles to condense into solid grains.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] In some star systems, dynamic processes in the protoplanetary disk can cause a gas giant to migrate much closer to the central star, creating a hot Jupiter.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Through gravitational interaction, the orbit of the planet becomes circularized and it is tidally locked into a synchronous rotation with one side constantly facing the star.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The heated side becomes swollen, and high velocity winds distribute the thermal energy around the planet.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The atmosphere may eventually be stripped away by the star's gravity, leaving behind a super Earth.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] At the upper mass extreme of gas giants is a class of objects known as brown dwarfs.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] There is no universal consensus on how to distinguish a brown dwarf from a gas giant, although a commonly used criteria is the ability to fuse deuterium at around 13 times the mass of Jupiter.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Once the initial deuterium burning phase of a brown dwarf is concluded, the internal store of heat gradually makes its way to the surface then is radiated away over time.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Convection occurs around the core, and possibly at the surface if the brown dwarf is receiving energy from a nearby star.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Radiative energy transfer occurs throughout the remainder of the brown dwarf.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Chemistry can occur throughout the atmosphere, which, depending on the chemical species, can change the opacity to radiative energy transfer.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] As with gas giants, in the cooler outer regions of a brown dwarf, some molecules can condense to form clouds.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The circulation of the atmosphere occurs due to thermal differences when convection becomes a more efficient transporter of heat than thermal radiation.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] On planets where the primary heat source is solar radiation, excess heat in the tropics is transported to higher latitudes.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] When a planet generates a significant amount of heat internally, such as is the case for Jupiter, convection in the atmosphere can transport thermal energy from the higher temperature interior up to the surface.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The thermally-driven meridional circulation of Earth, Mars, and Venus are dominated by the Hadley cell.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] This is created by rising air in the warmest region of the planet accompanied by descending air where it is cooler.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] However, there are significant differences in the circulation patterns between the three planets.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] For Venus, the lower atmosphere of Venus has two symmetrical equator to near pole circulation cells, with a higher altitude sub-solar to anti-solar circulation cell.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] On Earth, Hadley cells exist on each side of the equator, but these vary seasonally due to the planet's obliquity.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Mars is similar to the Earth in this respect, but it displays greater seasonality due to its thinner atmosphere.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] It has two Hadley cells during equinox, but a single cell at solstice.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The Earth has multiple counter-rotating convection cells, with the Hadley cell on either side of the equator, an intermediate Ferrel cell along the mid-latitudes, and polar cells at each pole.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The planet's rotation induces a Coriolis force that creates a curvature in the north-south convection flow.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] As air moves toward a pole, the latitudinal flow remains steady but the distance needed to encircle the planet grows shorter, creating a curved path along the surface.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] These flows create the prevailing winds along the planet's surface.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Near the equator, the air flow creates the trade winds which flow from east to west.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] At the mid-latitudes, the westerlies brings the air flow from the west in the United States and Europe.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Finally, the polar easterlies moves polar air from east to west.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Both Jupiter and Saturn display banded cloud formations.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] These are associated with alternating jets known as zonal flows that follow latitudinal lines.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The bands alternate in direction, with the equatorial jet moving eastward at 150 km/s on Jupiter and 300 km/s on Saturn.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] It remains unclear whether these flows occur in the shallow layers around the clouds, or extend much deeper into the atmosphere.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Observations of Neptune show a similar zonal flow structure.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] This planet displays the largest range of differential rotation in the Solar System.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Surface gravity differs significantly among the planets.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] For example, the large gravitational force of the giant planet Jupiter retains light gases such as hydrogen and helium that escape from objects with lower gravity.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Secondly, the distance from the Sun determines the energy available to heat atmospheric gas to the point where some fraction of its molecules' thermal motion exceed the planet's escape velocity, allowing those to escape a planet's gravitational grasp.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Thus, distant and cold Titan, Triton, and Pluto are able to retain components of their original atmospheres despite their relatively low gravities.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Since a collection of gas molecules may be moving at a wide range of velocities, there will always be some fast enough to produce a slow leakage of gas into space.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Lighter molecules move faster than heavier ones with the same thermal kinetic energy, and so gases of low molecular weight are lost more rapidly than those of high molecular weight.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] It is thought that Venus and Mars may have lost much of their water when, after being photodissociated into hydrogen and oxygen by solar ultraviolet radiation, the hydrogen escaped.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Earth's magnetic field helps to prevent this, as, normally, the solar wind would greatly enhance the escape of hydrogen.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] However, over the past 3 billion years Earth may have lost gases through the magnetic polar regions due to auroral activity, including a net 2% of its atmospheric oxygen.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The net effect, taking the most important escape processes into account, is that an intrinsic magnetic field does not protect a planet from atmospheric escape and that for some magnetizations the presence of a magnetic field works to increase the escape rate.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Planets around small M-type main-sequence stars may be particularly prone to atmospheric loss.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The star will spend an extended period as a superluminous pre-main-sequence star, then experience high levels of activity.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The strong stellar magnetic field will tend to reduce the size of planetary magnetospheres, leading to greater erosion from the stellar wind.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Planets around older M-type stars may become tidally locked in synchronous orbit, leading to the atmosphere being permanently frozen on the dark face.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Other mechanisms that can cause atmosphere depletion are solar wind-induced sputtering, impact erosion, weathering, and sequestration—sometimes referred to as "freezing out"—into the regolith and polar caps.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] An extreme example of the latter is a comet, which is a small body that forms beyond the frost line in the protoplanetary disk.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] These objects contain many types of frozen volatiles, including water, carbon dioxide, ammonia, methane, and formaldehyde.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] As these objects approach the Sun, the thermal radiation causes the volatiles to sublimate, creating a diffuse, dusty atmosphere around the comet; the coma.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] However, the gravitational potential of the comet is insufficient to retain this atmosphere.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] The Solar System contains a large number of bodies that are now practically airless, such as Mercury and the Moon.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] These objects have only an exosphere layer with particles that are essentially collisionless.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] In this environment, atoms and molecules are released from the surface by various means, including particle sputtering and micrometeorite impact.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] When the release velocity of these particles exceed the escape velocity, they are lost to space.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Higher mass particles have a greater chance to be returned to the surface, which creates a chemical alteration of the surface over time.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] On a terrestrial planet, the part of the atmosphere that directly interacts with the ground is known as the planetary boundary layer.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Atmospheres have dramatic effects on the surfaces of rocky bodies.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Wind erosion is a significant factor in shaping the terrain of rocky planets with atmospheres, and over time can erase the effects of both craters and volcanoes.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] In addition, since liquids cannot exist without pressure, an atmosphere allows liquid to be present at the surface, resulting in lakes, rivers and oceans.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Earth and Titan are known to have liquids at their surface and terrain on the planet Mars suggests that it had liquid on its surface in the past.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Objects that have no atmosphere, or that have only an exosphere, have terrain that is covered in craters.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Without an atmosphere, the planet has no protection from meteoroids, and all of them collide with the surface as meteorites and create craters.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] For planets with a significant atmosphere, most meteoroids burn up as meteors before hitting a planet's surface.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] When meteoroids do impact, the effects are often erased by the action of wind.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] From the perspective of a planetary geologist, the atmosphere acts to shape a planetary surface.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Wind picks up dust and other particles which, when they collide with the terrain, erode the relief and leave deposits (eolian processes).
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Frost and precipitations, which depend on the atmospheric composition, also influence the relief.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Climate changes can influence a planet's geological history.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] Conversely, studying the surface of the Earth leads to an understanding of the atmosphere and climate of other planets.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] For a meteorologist, the composition of the Earth's atmosphere is a factor affecting the climate and its variations.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] For a biologist or paleontologist, the Earth's atmospheric composition is closely dependent on the appearance of life and its evolution.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/atmosphere] In astrobiology, the composition of an exoplanet's atmosphere is closely intertwined with the possibility of extraterrestrial life.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Baron **Augustin-Louis Cauchy** (21 August 1789 – 23 May 1857) was a French mathematician, engineer, and physicist.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] He was one of the first to rigorously state and prove the key theorems of calculus (thereby creating real analysis), pioneered the field of complex analysis, and the study of permutation groups in abstract algebra.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Cauchy also contributed to a number of topics in mathematical physics, notably continuum mechanics.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Cauchy was a prolific worker; he wrote approximately eight hundred research articles and five complete textbooks on a variety of topics in the fields of mathematics and mathematical physics.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Cauchy was the son of Louis François Cauchy (1760–1848) and Marie-Madeleine Desestre.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Cauchy had two brothers: Alexandre Laurent Cauchy (1792–1857), who became a president of a division of the court of appeal in 1847 and a judge of the court of cassation in 1849, and Eugene François Cauchy (1802–1877), a publicist who also wrote several mathematical works.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] She was a close relative of the publisher who published most of Cauchy's works.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] They had two daughters, Marie Françoise Alicia (1819) and Marie Mathilde (1823).
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Cauchy's father was a highly ranked official in the Parisian police of the Ancien Régime, but lost this position due to the French Revolution (14 July 1789), which broke out one month before Augustin-Louis was born.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] The Cauchy family survived the revolution and the following Reign of Terror during 1793–94 by escaping to Arcueil, where Cauchy received his first education, from his father.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] After the execution of Robespierre in 1794, it was safe for the family to return to Paris.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] There, Louis-François Cauchy found a bureaucratic job in 1800, and quickly advanced his career.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] When Napoleon came to power in 1799, Louis-François Cauchy was further promoted, and became Secretary-General of the Senate, working directly under Laplace (who is now better known for his work on mathematical physics).
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] The mathematician Lagrange was also a friend of the Cauchy family.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] On Lagrange's advice, Augustin-Louis was enrolled in the École Centrale du Panthéon, the best secondary school of Paris at that time, in the fall of 1802.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Most of the curriculum consisted of classical languages; the ambitious Cauchy, being a brilliant student, won many prizes in Latin and the humanities.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] In spite of these successes, Cauchy chose an engineering career, and prepared himself for the entrance examination to the École Polytechnique.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] In 1805, he placed second of 293 applicants on this exam and was admitted.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] One of the main purposes of this school was to give future civil and military engineers a high-level scientific and mathematical education.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] The school functioned under military discipline, which caused Cauchy some problems in adapting.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Nevertheless, he completed the course in 1807, at age 18, and went on to the École des Ponts et Chaussées (School for Bridges and Roads).
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] He graduated in civil engineering, with the highest honors.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] After finishing school in 1810, Cauchy accepted a job as a junior engineer in Cherbourg, where Napoleon intended to build a naval base.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Here Cauchy stayed for three years, and was assigned the Ourcq Canal project and the Saint-Cloud Bridge project, and worked at the Harbor of Cherbourg.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Although he had an extremely busy managerial job, he still found time to prepare three mathematical manuscripts, which he submitted to the *Première Classe* (First Class) of the Institut de France.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Cauchy's first two manuscripts (on polyhedra) were accepted; the third one (on directrices of conic sections) was rejected.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] In September 1812, at 23 years old, Cauchy returned to Paris after becoming ill from overwork.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Another reason for his return to the capital was that he was losing interest in his engineering job, being more and more attracted to the abstract beauty of mathematics; in Paris, he would have a much better chance to find a mathematics related position.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] When his health improved in 1813, Cauchy chose not to return to Cherbourg.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Although he formally kept his engineering position, he was transferred from the payroll of the Ministry of the Marine to the Ministry of the Interior.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] The next three years Cauchy was mainly on unpaid sick leave; he spent his time fruitfully, working on mathematics (on the related topics of symmetric functions, the symmetric group and the theory of higher-order algebraic equations).
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] He attempted admission to the First Class of the Institut de France but failed on three different occasions between 1813 and 1815.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] In 1815 Napoleon was defeated at Waterloo, and the newly installed king Louis XVIII took the restoration in hand.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] The Académie des Sciences was re-established in March 1816; Lazare Carnot and Gaspard Monge were removed from this academy for political reasons, and the king appointed Cauchy to take the place of one of them.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] The reaction of Cauchy's peers was harsh; they considered the acceptance of his membership in the academy an outrage, and Cauchy created many enemies in scientific circles.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] In November 1815, Louis Poinsot, who was an associate professor at the École Polytechnique, asked to be exempted from his teaching duties for health reasons.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Cauchy was by then a rising mathematical star.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] One of his great successes at that time was the proof of Fermat's polygonal number theorem.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] He quit his engineering job, and received a one-year contract for teaching mathematics to second-year students of the École Polytechnique.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] In 1816, this Bonapartist, non-religious school was reorganized, and several liberal professors were fired; Cauchy was promoted to full professor.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] When Cauchy was 28 years old, he was still living with his parents.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] His father found it time for his son to marry; he found him a suitable bride, Aloïse de Bure, five years his junior.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] The de Bure family were printers and booksellers, and published most of Cauchy's works.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Aloïse and Augustin were married on April 4, 1818, with great Roman Catholic ceremony, in the Church of Saint-Sulpice.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] In 1819 the couple's first daughter, Marie Françoise Alicia, was born, and in 1823 the second and last daughter, Marie Mathilde.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] The conservative political climate that lasted until 1830 suited Cauchy perfectly.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] In 1824 Louis XVIII died, and was succeeded by his even more conservative brother Charles X.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] During these years Cauchy was highly productive, and published one important mathematical treatise after another.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] He received cross-appointments at the Collège de France, and the Faculté des sciences de Paris.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] In July 1830, the July Revolution occurred in France.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Charles X fled the country, and was succeeded by Louis Philippe I.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Riots, in which uniformed students of the École Polytechnique took an active part, raged close to Cauchy's home in Paris.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] These events marked a turning point in Cauchy's life, and a break in his mathematical productivity.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Shaken by the fall of the government and moved by a deep hatred of the liberals who were taking power, Cauchy left France to go abroad, leaving his family behind.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] He spent a short time at Fribourg in Switzerland, where he had to decide whether he would swear a required oath of allegiance to the new regime.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] He refused to do this, and consequently lost all his positions in Paris, except his membership of the academy, for which an oath was not required.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] In 1831 Cauchy went to the Italian city of Turin, and after some time there, he accepted an offer from the King of Sardinia (who ruled Turin and the surrounding Piedmont region) for a chair of theoretical physics, which was created especially for him.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] In 1831, he was elected a foreign member of the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences, and the following year a Foreign Honorary Member of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] In August 1833 Cauchy left Turin for Prague to become the science tutor of the thirteen-year-old Duke of Bordeaux, Henri d'Artois (1820–1883), the exiled Crown Prince and grandson of Charles X.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] As a professor of the École Polytechnique, Cauchy had been a notoriously bad lecturer, assuming levels of understanding that only a few of his best students could reach, and cramming his allotted time with too much material.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Henri d'Artois had neither taste nor talent for either mathematics or science.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Although Cauchy took his mission very seriously, he did this with great clumsiness, and with surprising lack of authority over Henri d'Artois.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] During his civil engineering days, Cauchy once had been briefly in charge of repairing a few of the Parisian sewers, and he made the mistake of mentioning this to his pupil; with great malice, Henri d'Artois went about saying Cauchy started his career in the sewers of Paris.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Cauchy's role as tutor lasted until Henri d'Artois became eighteen years old, in September 1838.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Cauchy did hardly any research during those five years, while Henri d'Artois acquired a lifelong dislike of mathematics.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Cauchy was named a baron, a title by which Cauchy set great store.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] In 1834, his wife and two daughters moved to Prague, and Cauchy was reunited with his family after four years in exile.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Cauchy returned to Paris and his position at the Academy of Sciences late in 1838.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] He could not regain his teaching positions, because he still refused to swear an oath of allegiance.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] In August 1839 a vacancy appeared in the Bureau des Longitudes.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] This Bureau bore some resemblance to the academy; for instance, it had the right to co-opt its members.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Further, it was believed that members of the Bureau could "forget about" the oath of allegiance, although formally, unlike the Academicians, they were obliged to take it.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] The Bureau des Longitudes was an organization founded in 1795 to solve the problem of determining position at sea — mainly the longitudinal coordinate, since latitude is easily determined from the position of the sun.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Since it was thought that position at sea was best determined by astronomical observations, the Bureau had developed into an organization resembling an academy of astronomical sciences.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] In November 1839 Cauchy was elected to the Bureau, and discovered that the matter of the oath was not so easily dispensed with.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Without his oath, the king refused to approve his election.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] For four years Cauchy was in the position of being elected but not approved; accordingly, he was not a formal member of the Bureau, did not receive payment, could not participate in meetings, and could not submit papers.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Still Cauchy refused to take any oaths; however, he did feel loyal enough to direct his research to celestial mechanics.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] In 1840, he presented a dozen papers on this topic to the academy.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] He described and illustrated the signed-digit representation of numbers, an innovation presented in England in 1727 by John Colson.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] The confounded membership of the Bureau lasted until the end of 1843, when Cauchy was replaced by Poinsot.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Throughout the nineteenth century the French educational system struggled over the separation of church and state.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] After losing control of the public education system, the Catholic Church sought to establish its own branch of education and found in Cauchy a staunch and illustrious ally.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] He lent his prestige and knowledge to the École Normale Écclésiastique, a school in Paris run by Jesuits, for training teachers for their colleges.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] He took part in the founding of the Institut Catholique.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] The purpose of this institute was to counter the effects of the absence of Catholic university education in France.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] These activities did not make Cauchy popular with his colleagues, who, on the whole, supported the Enlightenment ideals of the French Revolution.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] When a chair of mathematics became vacant at the Collège de France in 1843, Cauchy applied for it, but received just three of 45 votes.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] In 1848 King Louis-Philippe fled to England.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] The oath of allegiance was abolished, and the road to an academic appointment was clear for Cauchy.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] On March 1, 1849, he was reinstated at the Faculté de Sciences, as a professor of mathematical astronomy.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] After political turmoil all through 1848, France chose to become a Republic, under the Presidency of Napoleon III of France.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Early 1852 the President made himself Emperor of France, and took the name Napoleon III.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] The idea came up in bureaucratic circles that it would be useful to again require a loyalty oath from all state functionaries, including university professors.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] This time a cabinet minister was able to convince the Emperor to exempt Cauchy from the oath.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] In 1853, Cauchy was elected an International Member of the American Philosophical Society.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Cauchy remained a professor at the university until his death at the age of 67.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] He received the Last Rites and died of a bronchial condition at 4 a.m. on 23 May 1857.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] His name is one of the 72 names inscribed on the Eiffel Tower.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] The genius of Cauchy was illustrated in his simple solution of the problem of Apollonius—describing a circle touching three given circles—which he discovered in 1805, his generalization of Euler's formula on polyhedra in 1811, and in several other elegant problems.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] More important is his memoir on wave propagation, which obtained the Grand Prix of the French Academy of Sciences in 1816.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Cauchy's writings covered notable topics.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] In the theory of series he developed the notion of convergence and discovered many of the basic formulas for q-series.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] In the theory of numbers and complex quantities, he was the first to define complex numbers as pairs of real numbers.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] He also wrote on the theory of groups and substitutions, the theory of functions, differential equations and determinants.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] In the theory of light he worked on Fresnel's wave theory and on the dispersion and polarization of light.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] He also contributed research in mechanics, substituting the notion of the continuity of geometrical displacements for the principle of the continuity of matter.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] He wrote on the equilibrium of rods and elastic membranes and on waves in elastic media.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] He introduced a 3 × 3 symmetric matrix of numbers that is now known as the Cauchy stress tensor.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] In elasticity, he originated the theory of stress, and his results are nearly as valuable as those of Siméon Poisson.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Other significant contributions include being the first to prove the Fermat polygonal number theorem.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Cauchy is most famous for his single-handed development of complex function theory.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] where *f*(*z*) is a complex-valued function holomorphic on and within the non-self-intersecting closed curve *C* (contour) lying in the complex plane.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] The *contour integral* is taken along the contour *C*.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] The rudiments of this theorem can already be found in a paper that the 24-year-old Cauchy presented to the Académie des Sciences (then still called "First Class of the Institute") on August 11, 1814.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] In full form the theorem was given in 1825.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] In 1826 Cauchy gave a formal definition of a residue of a function.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] This concept concerns functions that have poles—isolated singularities, i.e., points where a function goes to positive or negative infinity.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] where φ(*z*) is analytic (i.e., well-behaved without singularities), then *f* is said to have a pole of order *n* in the point *a*.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] The coefficient *B*1 is called by Cauchy the residue of function *f* at *a*.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] If *f* is non-singular at *a* then the residue of *f* is zero at *a*.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] where we replaced *B*1 by the modern notation of the residue.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] In 1831, while in Turin, Cauchy submitted two papers to the Academy of Sciences of Turin.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] where *f*(*z*) is analytic on *C* and within the region bounded by the contour *C* and the complex number *a* is somewhere in this region.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] The contour integral is taken counter-clockwise.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Clearly, the integrand has a simple pole at *z* = *a*.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] where the sum is over all the *n* poles of *f*(*z*) on and within the contour *C*.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] These results of Cauchy's still form the core of complex function theory as it is taught today to physicists and electrical engineers.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] For quite some time, contemporaries of Cauchy ignored his theory, believing it to be too complicated.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Only in the 1840s the theory started to get response, with Pierre Alphonse Laurent being the first mathematician besides Cauchy to make a substantial contribution (his work on what are now known as Laurent series, published in 1843).
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] In his book *Cours d'analyse* Cauchy stressed the importance of rigor in analysis.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] *Rigor* in this case meant the rejection of the principle of *Generality of algebra* (of earlier authors such as Euler and Lagrange) and its replacement by geometry and infinitesimals.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Judith Grabiner wrote Cauchy was "the man who taught rigorous analysis to all of Europe".
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] The book is frequently noted as being the first place that inequalities, and $\delta -\varepsilon$ arguments were introduced into calculus.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Barany claims that the École mandated the inclusion of infinitesimal methods against Cauchy's better judgement.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Gilain notes that when the portion of the curriculum devoted to *Analyse Algébrique* was reduced in 1825, Cauchy insisted on placing the topic of continuous functions (and therefore also infinitesimals) at the beginning of the Differential Calculus.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Laugwitz (1989) and Benis-Sinaceur (1973) point out that Cauchy continued to use infinitesimals in his own research as late as 1853.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Cauchy gave an explicit definition of an infinitesimal in terms of a sequence tending to zero.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] There has been a vast body of literature written about Cauchy's notion of "infinitesimally small quantities", arguing that they lead from everything from the usual "epsilontic" definitions or to the notions of non-standard analysis.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] The consensus is that Cauchy omitted or left implicit the important ideas to make clear the precise meaning of the infinitely small quantities he used.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] He was the first to prove Taylor's theorem rigorously, establishing his well-known form of the remainder.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] He wrote a textbook (see the illustration) for his students at the École Polytechnique in which he developed the basic theorems of mathematical analysis as rigorously as possible.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] In this book he gave the necessary and sufficient condition for the existence of a limit in the form that is still taught.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Also Cauchy's well-known test for absolute convergence stems from this book: Cauchy condensation test.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] In 1829 he defined for the first time a complex function of a complex variable in another textbook.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] In spite of these, Cauchy's own research papers often used intuitive, not rigorous, methods; thus one of his theorems was exposed to a "counter-example" by Abel, later fixed by the introduction of the notion of uniform continuity.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] In a paper published in 1855, two years before Cauchy's death, he discussed some theorems, one of which is similar to the "Principle of the argument" in many modern textbooks on complex analysis.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] In modern control theory textbooks, the Cauchy argument principle is quite frequently used to derive the Nyquist stability criterion, which can be used to predict the stability of negative feedback amplifier and negative feedback control systems.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Thus Cauchy's work has a strong impact on both pure mathematics and practical engineering.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Cauchy was very productive, in number of papers second only to Leonhard Euler.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Augustin-Louis Cauchy grew up in the house of a staunch royalist.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] This made his father flee with the family to Arcueil during the French Revolution.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Their life there during that time was apparently hard; Augustin-Louis's father, Louis François, spoke of living on rice, bread, and crackers during the period.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] In any event, he inherited his father's staunch royalism and hence refused to take oaths to any government after the overthrow of Charles X.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] He was an equally staunch Catholic and a member of the Society of Saint Vincent de Paul.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] He also had links to the Society of Jesus and defended them at the academy when it was politically unwise to do so.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] His zeal for his faith may have led to his caring for Charles Hermite during his illness and leading Hermite to become a faithful Catholic.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] It also inspired Cauchy to plead on behalf of the Irish during the Great Famine of Ireland.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] His royalism and religious zeal made him contentious, which caused difficulties with his colleagues.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] He felt that he was mistreated for his beliefs, but his opponents felt he intentionally provoked people by berating them over religious matters or by defending the Jesuits after they had been suppressed.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Niels Henrik Abel called him a "bigoted Catholic" and added he was "mad and there is nothing that can be done about him", but at the same time praised him as a mathematician.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Cauchy's views were widely unpopular among mathematicians and when Guglielmo Libri Carucci dalla Sommaja was made chair in mathematics before him he, and many others, felt his views were the cause.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] When Libri was accused of stealing books he was replaced by Joseph Liouville rather than Cauchy, which caused a rift between Liouville and Cauchy.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Another dispute with political overtones concerned Jean-Marie Constant Duhamel and a claim on inelastic shocks.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/augustin-louis-cauchy] Cauchy was later shown, by Jean-Victor Poncelet, to be wrong.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] In applied mechanics, **bending** (also known as **flexure**) characterizes the behavior of a slender structural element subjected to an external load applied perpendicularly to a longitudinal axis of the element.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] The structural element is assumed to be such that at least one of its dimensions is a small fraction, typically 1/10 or less, of the other two.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] When the length is considerably longer than the width and the thickness, the element is called a beam.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] For example, a closet rod sagging under the weight of clothes on clothes hangers is an example of a beam experiencing bending.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] On the other hand, a shell is a structure of any geometric form where the length and the width are of the same order of magnitude but the thickness of the structure (known as the 'wall') is considerably smaller.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] A large diameter, but thin-walled, short tube supported at its ends and loaded laterally is an example of a shell experiencing bending.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] In the absence of a qualifier, the term *bending* is ambiguous because bending can occur locally in all objects.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] Therefore, to make the usage of the term more precise, engineers refer to a specific object such as; the *bending of rods*, the *bending of beams*, the *bending of plates*, the *bending of shells* and so on.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] A beam deforms and stresses develop inside it when a transverse load is applied on it.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] In the quasi-static case, the amount of bending deflection and the stresses that develop are assumed not to change over time.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] In a horizontal beam supported at the ends and loaded downwards in the middle, the material at the over-side of the beam is compressed while the material at the underside is stretched.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] These last two forces form a couple or moment as they are equal in magnitude and opposite in direction.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] This bending moment resists the sagging deformation characteristic of a beam experiencing bending.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] The stress distribution in a beam can be predicted quite accurately when some simplifying assumptions are used.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] In the Euler–Bernoulli theory of slender beams, a major assumption is that 'plane sections remain plane'.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] In other words, any deformation due to shear across the section is not accounted for (no shear deformation).
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] Also, this linear distribution is only applicable if the maximum stress is less than the yield stress of the material.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] For stresses that exceed yield, refer to article plastic bending.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] At yield, the maximum stress experienced in the section (at the furthest points from the neutral axis of the beam) is defined as the flexural strength.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] where the second derivative of its deflected shape with respect to x is interpreted as its curvature, E is the Young's modulus, I is the area moment of inertia of the cross-section, and M is the internal bending moment in the beam.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] This is the Euler–Bernoulli equation for beam bending.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] Simple beam bending is often analyzed with the Euler–Bernoulli beam equation.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] The material is isotropic (or orthotropic) and homogeneous.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] The material obeys Hooke's law (it is linearly elastic and will not deform plastically).
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] The beam is initially straight with a cross section that is constant throughout the beam length.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] The beam has an axis of symmetry in the plane of bending.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] The proportions of the beam are such that it would fail by bending rather than by crushing, wrinkling or sideways buckling.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] Cross-sections of the beam remain plane during bending.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] Compressive and tensile forces develop in the direction of the beam axis under bending loads.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] These forces induce stresses on the beam.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] The maximum compressive stress is found at the uppermost edge of the beam while the maximum tensile stress is located at the lower edge of the beam.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] Since the stresses between these two opposing maxima vary linearly, there therefore exists a point on the linear path between them where there is no bending stress.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] The locus of these points is the neutral axis.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] Because of this area with no stress and the adjacent areas with low stress, using uniform cross section beams in bending is not a particularly efficient means of supporting a load as it does not use the full capacity of the beam until it is on the brink of collapse.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] Wide-flange beams (Ɪ-beams) and truss girders effectively address this inefficiency as they minimize the amount of material in this under-stressed region.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] The equation $\sigma ={\tfrac {My}{I_{x}}}$ is valid only when the stress at the extreme fiber (i.e., the portion of the beam farthest from the neutral axis) is below the yield stress of the material from which it is constructed.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] This plastic hinge state is typically used as a limit state in the design of steel structures.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] The equation above is only valid if the cross-section is symmetrical.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] Using this equation it is possible to calculate the bending stress at any point on the beam cross section regardless of moment orientation or cross-sectional shape.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] Note that $M_{y},M_{z},I_{y},I_{z},I_{yz}$ do not change from one point to another on the cross section.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] For large deformations of the body, the stress in the cross-section is calculated using an extended version of this formula.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] Shear and normal stresses in this section that are perpendicular to the normal vector of cross section have no influence on normal stresses that are parallel to this section.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] In 1921, Timoshenko improved upon the Euler–Bernoulli theory of beams by adding the effect of shear into the beam equation.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] However, normals to the axis are not required to remain perpendicular to the axis after deformation.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] where I is the area moment of inertia of the cross-section, A is the cross-sectional area, G is the shear modulus, k is a **shear correction factor**, and $q(x)$ is an applied transverse load.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] According to Euler–Bernoulli, Timoshenko or other bending theories, the beams on elastic foundations can be explained.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] The dynamic bending of beams, also known as flexural vibrations of beams, was first investigated by Daniel Bernoulli in the late 18th century.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] Bernoulli's equation of motion of a vibrating beam tended to overestimate the natural frequencies of beams and was improved marginally by Rayleigh in 1877 by the addition of a mid-plane rotation.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] In 1921 Stephen Timoshenko improved the theory further by incorporating the effect of shear on the dynamic response of bending beams.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] This allowed the theory to be used for problems involving high frequencies of vibration where the dynamic Euler–Bernoulli theory is inadequate.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] The Euler-Bernoulli and Timoshenko theories for the dynamic bending of beams continue to be used widely by engineers.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] where E is the Young's modulus, I is the area moment of inertia of the cross-section, $w(x,t)$ is the deflection of the neutral axis of the beam, and m is mass per unit length of the beam.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] In 1877, Rayleigh proposed an improvement to the dynamic Euler–Bernoulli beam theory by including the effect of rotational inertia of the cross-section of the beam.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] Timoshenko improved upon that theory in 1922 by adding the effect of shear into the beam equation.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] Shear deformations of the normal to the mid-surface of the beam are allowed in the Timoshenko–Rayleigh theory.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] where $J={\tfrac {mI}{A}}$ is the polar moment of inertia of the cross-section, $m=\rho A$ is the mass per unit length of the beam, $\rho$ is the density of the beam, A is the cross-sectional area, G is the shear modulus, and k is a **shear correction factor**.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] This equation can be solved by noting that all the derivatives of w must have the same form to cancel out and hence as solution of the form $e^{kx}$ may be expected.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] The defining feature of beams is that one of the dimensions is much *larger* than the other two.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] A structure is called a plate when it is flat and one of its dimensions is much *smaller* than the other two.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] There are several theories that attempt to describe the deformation and stress in a plate under applied loads two of which have been used widely.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] where $\mathbf {u}$ is the displacement of a point in the plate and $w^{0}$ is the displacement of the mid-surface.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] where $q(x)$ is an applied load normal to the surface of the plate.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] The special assumption of this theory is that normals to the mid-surface remain straight and inextensible but not necessarily normal to the mid-surface after deformation.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] where $\varphi _{\alpha }$ are the rotations of the normal.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] where $\kappa$ is a shear correction factor.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] The dynamic theory of plates determines the propagation of waves in the plates, and the study of standing waves and vibration modes.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bending] The figures below show some vibrational modes of a circular plate.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Bernoulli's principle can be derived from the principle of conservation of energy.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] This states that, in a steady flow, the sum of all forms of energy in a fluid is the same at all points that are free of viscous forces.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] This requires that the sum of kinetic energy, potential energy and internal energy remains constant.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Thus an increase in the speed of the fluid—implying an increase in its kinetic energy—occurs with a simultaneous decrease in (the sum of) its potential energy (including the static pressure) and internal energy.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] If the fluid is flowing out of a reservoir, the sum of all forms of energy is the same because in a reservoir the energy per unit volume (the sum of pressure and gravitational potential *ρ* *g* *h*) is the same everywhere.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Bernoulli's principle can also be derived directly from Isaac Newton's second law of motion.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] When a fluid is flowing horizontally from a region of high pressure to a region of low pressure, there is more pressure from behind than in front.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] This gives a net force on the volume, accelerating it along the streamline.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Fluid particles are subject only to pressure and their own weight.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Consequently, within a fluid flowing horizontally, the highest speed occurs where the pressure is lowest, and the lowest speed occurs where the pressure is highest.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Bernoulli's principle is only applicable for isentropic flows: when the effects of irreversible processes (like turbulence) and non-adiabatic processes (e.g. thermal radiation) are small and can be neglected.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] However, the principle can be applied to various types of flow within these bounds, resulting in various forms of Bernoulli's equation.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] The simple form of Bernoulli's equation is valid for incompressible flows (e.g. most liquid flows and gases moving at low Mach number).
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] More advanced forms may be applied to compressible flows at higher Mach numbers.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] In most flows of liquids, and of gases at low Mach number, the density of a fluid parcel can be considered to be constant, regardless of pressure variations in the flow.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Therefore, the fluid can be considered to be incompressible, and these flows are called incompressible flows.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Bernoulli performed his experiments on liquids, so his equation in its original form is valid only for incompressible flow.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Bernoulli's equation and the Bernoulli constant are applicable throughout any region of flow where the energy per unit mass is uniform.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] For conservative force fields (not limited to the gravitational field), Bernoulli's equation can be generalized as: ${\frac {v^{2}}{2}}+\Psi +{\frac {p}{\rho }}={\text{constant}}$ where Ψ is the force potential at the point considered.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] For example, for the Earth's gravity Ψ = *gz*.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] The constant in the Bernoulli equation can be normalized.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] The above equations suggest there is a flow speed at which pressure is zero, and at even higher speeds the pressure is negative.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Most often, gases and liquids are not capable of negative absolute pressure, or even zero pressure, so clearly Bernoulli's equation ceases to be valid before zero pressure is reached.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] In liquids—when the pressure becomes too low—cavitation occurs.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] The above equations use a linear relationship between flow speed squared and pressure.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] At higher flow speeds in gases, or for sound waves in liquid, the changes in mass density become significant so that the assumption of constant density is invalid.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] In many applications of Bernoulli's equation, the change in the ρgz term is so small compared with the other terms that it can be ignored.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] For example, in the case of aircraft in flight, the change in height z is so small the ρgz term can be omitted.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] This allows the above equation to be presented in the following simplified form: $p+q=p_{0}$ where *p*0 is called ***total pressure***, and q is *dynamic pressure*.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Many authors refer to the pressure p as static pressure to distinguish it from total pressure *p*0 and dynamic pressure q.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Static pressure + Dynamic pressure = Total pressure.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Every point in a steadily flowing fluid, regardless of the fluid speed at that point, has its own unique static pressure p and dynamic pressure q.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Their sum *p* + *q* is defined to be the total pressure *p*0.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] The significance of Bernoulli's principle can now be summarized as "total pressure is constant in any region free of viscous forces".
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] If the fluid flow is brought to rest at some point, this point is called a stagnation point, and at this point the static pressure is equal to the stagnation pressure.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] If the fluid flow is irrotational, the total pressure is uniform and Bernoulli's principle can be summarized as "total pressure is constant everywhere in the fluid flow".
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] It is reasonable to assume that irrotational flow exists in any situation where a large body of fluid is flowing past a solid body.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Examples are aircraft in flight and ships moving in open bodies of water.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] However, Bernoulli's principle importantly does not apply in the boundary layer such as in flow through long pipes.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] The Bernoulli equation for unsteady potential flow is used in the theory of ocean surface waves and acoustics.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] For an irrotational flow, the flow velocity can be described as the gradient ∇*φ* of a velocity potential φ.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] which is a Bernoulli equation valid also for unsteady—or time dependent—flows.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Here ⁠∂*φ*/∂*t*⁠ denotes the partial derivative of the velocity potential φ with respect to time t, and *v* = |∇*φ*| is the flow speed.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] The function *f*(*t*) depends only on time and not on position in the fluid.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] As a result, the Bernoulli equation at some moment t applies in the whole fluid domain.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] This is also true for the special case of a steady irrotational flow, in which case f and ⁠∂*φ*/∂*t*⁠ are constants so equation (**A**) can be applied in every point of the fluid domain.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Note that the relation of the potential to the flow velocity is unaffected by this transformation: ∇Φ = ∇*φ*.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] The Bernoulli equation for unsteady potential flow also appears to play a central role in Luke's variational principle, a variational description of free-surface flows using the Lagrangian mechanics.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Bernoulli developed his principle from observations on liquids, and Bernoulli's equation is valid for ideal fluids: those that are inviscid, incompressible and subjected only to conservative forces.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] It is sometimes valid for the flow of gases as well, provided that there is no transfer of kinetic or potential energy from the gas flow to the compression or expansion of the gas.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] If both the gas pressure and volume change simultaneously, then work will be done on or by the gas.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] In this case, Bernoulli's equation in its incompressible flow form cannot be assumed to be valid.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] However, if the gas process is entirely isobaric, or isochoric, then no work is done on or by the gas (so the simple energy balance is not upset).
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] According to the gas law, an isobaric or isochoric process is ordinarily the only way to ensure constant density in a gas.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Also the gas density will be proportional to the ratio of pressure and absolute temperature; however, this ratio will vary upon compression or expansion, no matter what non-zero quantity of heat is added or removed.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] The only exception is if the net heat transfer is zero, as in a complete thermodynamic cycle or in an individual isentropic (frictionless adiabatic) process, and even then this reversible process must be reversed, to restore the gas to the original pressure and specific volume, and thus density.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Only then is the original, unmodified Bernoulli equation applicable.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] In this case the equation can be used if the flow speed of the gas is sufficiently below the speed of sound, such that the variation in density of the gas (due to this effect) along each streamline can be ignored.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Adiabatic flow at less than Mach 0.3 is generally considered to be slow enough.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] It is possible to use the fundamental principles of physics to develop similar equations applicable to compressible fluids.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] There are numerous equations, each tailored for a particular application, but all are analogous to Bernoulli's equation and all rely on nothing more than the fundamental principles of physics such as Newton's laws of motion or the first law of thermodynamics.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] In engineering situations, elevations are generally small compared to the size of the Earth, and the time scales of fluid flow are small enough to consider the equation of state as adiabatic.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] In many applications of compressible flow, changes in elevation are negligible compared to the other terms, so the term gz can be omitted.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Here w is the enthalpy per unit mass (also known as specific enthalpy), which is also often written as h (not to be confused with "head" or "height").
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Note that $w=e+{\frac {p}{\rho }}~~~\left(={\frac {\gamma }{\gamma -1}}{\frac {p}{\rho }}\right)$ where e is the thermodynamic energy per unit mass, also known as the specific internal energy.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] So, for constant internal energy e the equation reduces to the incompressible-flow form.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] The constant on the right-hand side is often called the Bernoulli constant and denoted b.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] For steady inviscid adiabatic flow with no additional sources or sinks of energy, b is constant along any given streamline.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] More generally, when b may vary along streamlines, it still proves a useful parameter, related to the "head" of the fluid (see below).
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] When the change in Ψ can be ignored, a very useful form of this equation is: ${\frac {v^{2}}{2}}+w=w_{0}$ where *w*0 is total enthalpy.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] For a calorically perfect gas such as an ideal gas, the enthalpy is directly proportional to the temperature, and this leads to the concept of the total (or stagnation) temperature.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] When shock waves are present, in a reference frame in which the shock is stationary and the flow is steady, many of the parameters in the Bernoulli equation suffer abrupt changes in passing through the shock.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] The Bernoulli parameter remains unaffected.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] An exception to this rule is radiative shocks, which violate the assumptions leading to the Bernoulli equation, namely the lack of additional sinks or sources of energy.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] With the irrotational assumption, namely, the flow velocity can be described as the gradient ∇*φ* of a velocity potential *φ*.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] The Bernoulli equation for incompressible fluids can be derived by either integrating Newton's second law of motion or by applying the law of conservation of energy, ignoring viscosity, compressibility, and thermal effects.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] The simplest derivation is to first ignore gravity and consider constrictions and expansions in pipes that are otherwise straight, as seen in Venturi effect.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Let the x axis be directed down the axis of the pipe.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Define a parcel of fluid moving through a pipe with cross-sectional area A, the length of the parcel is d*x*, and the volume of the parcel *A* d*x*.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] If mass density is ρ, the mass of the parcel is density multiplied by its volume *m* = *ρA* d*x*.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] The change in pressure over distance d*x* is d*p* and flow velocity *v* = ⁠d*x*/d*t*⁠.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Apply Newton's second law of motion (force = mass × acceleration) and recognizing that the effective force on the parcel of fluid is −*A* d*p*.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] If the pressure decreases along the length of the pipe, d*p* is negative but the force resulting in flow is positive along the x axis.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] In steady flow the velocity field is constant with respect to time, *v* = *v*(*x*) = *v*(*x*(*t*)), so v itself is not directly a function of time t.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] With density ρ constant, the equation of motion can be written as ${\frac {\mathrm {d} }{\mathrm {d} x}}\left(\rho {\frac {v^{2}}{2}}+p\right)=0$ by integrating with respect to x ${\frac {v^{2}}{2}}+{\frac {p}{\rho }}=C$ where C is a constant, sometimes referred to as the Bernoulli constant.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] It is not a universal constant, but rather a constant of a particular fluid system.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] The deduction is: where the speed is large, pressure is low and vice versa.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] In the above derivation, no external work–energy principle is invoked.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Rather, Bernoulli's principle was derived by a simple manipulation of Newton's second law.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Another way to derive Bernoulli's principle for an incompressible flow is by applying conservation of energy.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] The system consists of the volume of fluid, initially between the cross-sections *A*1 and *A*2.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] In the time interval Δ*t* fluid elements initially at the inflow cross-section *A*1 move over a distance *s*1 = *v*1 Δ*t*, while at the outflow cross-section the fluid moves away from cross-section *A*2 over a distance *s*2 = *v*2 Δ*t*.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] The displaced fluid volumes at the inflow and outflow are respectively *A*1*s*1 and *A*2*s*2.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] The associated displaced fluid masses are – when ρ is the fluid's mass density – equal to density times volume, so *ρA*1*s*1 and *ρA*2*s*2.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Further division by g produces the following equation.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Note that each term can be described in the length dimension (such as meters).
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] The middle term, z, represents the potential energy of the fluid due to its elevation with respect to a reference plane.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Now, z is called the elevation head and given the designation *z*elevation.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] A free falling mass from an elevation *z* > 0 (in a vacuum) will reach a speed $v={\sqrt {{2g}{z}}},$ when arriving at elevation *z* = 0.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Or when rearranged as *head*: $h_{v}={\frac {v^{2}}{2g}}$ The term ⁠*v*2/2*g*⁠ is called the *velocity head*, expressed as a length measurement.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] It represents the internal energy of the fluid due to its motion.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] The hydrostatic pressure *p* is defined as $p=p_{0}-\rho gz,$ with *p*0 some reference pressure, or when rearranged as *head*: $\psi ={\frac {p}{\rho g}}.$ The term ⁠*p*/*ρg*⁠ is also called the *pressure head*, expressed as a length measurement.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] It represents the internal energy of the fluid due to the pressure exerted on the container.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] The head due to the flow speed and the head due to static pressure combined with the elevation above a reference plane, a simple relationship useful for incompressible fluids using the velocity head, elevation head, and pressure head is obtained.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Note that the pressure of the system is constant in this form of the Bernoulli equation.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] If the static pressure of the system (the third term) increases, and if the pressure due to elevation (the middle term) is constant, then the dynamic pressure (the first term) must have decreased.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] In other words, if the speed of a fluid decreases and it is not due to an elevation difference, it must be due to an increase in the static pressure that is resisting the flow.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] All three equations are merely simplified versions of an energy balance on a system.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] The derivation for compressible fluids is similar.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Again, the derivation depends upon (1) conservation of mass, and (2) conservation of energy.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Clearly, in a more complicated situation such as a fluid flow coupled with radiation, such conditions are not met.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Nevertheless, assuming this to be the case and assuming the flow is steady so that the net change in the energy is zero, $\Delta E_{1}-\Delta E_{2}=0$ where Δ*E*1 and Δ*E*2 are the energy entering through *A*1 and leaving through *A*2, respectively.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] A similar expression for Δ*E*2 may easily be constructed.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] In modern everyday life there are many observations that can be successfully explained by application of Bernoulli's principle, even though no real fluid is entirely inviscid, and a small viscosity often has a large effect on the flow.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Bernoulli's principle is then cited to conclude that the pressure on top of the wing must be lower than on the bottom.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Equal transit time applies to the flow around a body generating no lift, but there is no physical principle that requires equal transit time in cases of bodies generating lift.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] In fact, theory predicts – and experiments confirm – that the air traverses the top surface of a body experiencing lift in a *shorter* time than it traverses the bottom surface; the explanation based on equal transit time is false.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] While the equal-time explanation is false, it is not the Bernoulli principle that is false, because this principle is well established; Bernoulli's equation is used correctly in common mathematical treatments of aerodynamic lift.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] There are several common classroom demonstrations that are sometimes incorrectly explained using Bernoulli's principle.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] One involves holding a piece of paper horizontally so that it droops downward and then blowing over the top of it.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] As the demonstrator blows over the paper, the paper rises.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] It is then asserted that this is because "faster moving air has lower pressure".
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] One problem with this explanation can be seen by blowing along the bottom of the paper: if the deflection was caused by faster moving air, then the paper should deflect downward; but the paper deflects upward regardless of whether the faster moving air is on the top or the bottom.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] A third problem is that it is false to make a connection between the flow on the two sides of the paper using Bernoulli's equation since the air above and below are *different* flow fields and Bernoulli's principle only applies within a flow field.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] As the wording of the principle can change its implications, stating the principle correctly is important.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] What Bernoulli's principle actually says is that within a flow of constant energy, when fluid flows through a region of lower pressure it speeds up and vice versa.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Thus, Bernoulli's principle concerns itself with *changes* in speed and *changes* in pressure *within* a flow field.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] It cannot be used to compare different flow fields.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] A correct explanation of why the paper rises would observe that the plume follows the curve of the paper and that a curved streamline will develop a pressure gradient perpendicular to the direction of flow, with the lower pressure on the inside of the curve.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Bernoulli's principle predicts that the decrease in pressure is associated with an increase in speed; in other words, as the air passes over the paper, it speeds up and moves faster than it was moving when it left the demonstrator's mouth.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] But this is not apparent from the demonstration.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/bernoulli-s-principle] Other common classroom demonstrations, such as blowing between two suspended spheres, inflating a large bag, or suspending a ball in an airstream are sometimes explained in a similarly misleading manner by saying "faster moving air has lower pressure".
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics] In physics, the first law of thermodynamics is an expression of the conservation of total energy of a system.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics] Because it expresses conservation of total energy, this is sometimes referred to as the **energy balance equation** of continuous media.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics] The first law is used to derive the non-conservation form of the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics] That is, pulling is positive stress and pushing is negative stress.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics] That is, the change in the internal energy of the substance within a volume is the negative of the amount carried out of the volume by the flow of material across the boundary plus the work done compressing the material on the boundary minus the flow of heat out through the boundary.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics] More generally, it is possible to incorporate source terms.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics] where h is specific enthalpy, $\Phi ={\mathbf {\tau } }:\nabla {\mathbf {v} }$ is dissipation function and T is temperature.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics] i.e. internal energy per unit volume equals mass density times the sum of: proper energy per unit mass, kinetic energy per unit mass, and gravitational potential energy per unit mass.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics] i.e. change in heat per unit volume (negative divergence of heat flow) equals the divergence of heat conductivity times the gradient of the temperature.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics] i.e. divergence of work done against stress equals flow of material times divergence of stress plus stress times divergence of material flow.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics] i.e. stress times divergence of material flow equals deviatoric stress tensor times divergence of material flow minus pressure times material flow.
[src:first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics/first-law-of-thermodynamics-fluid-mechanics] i.e. enthalpy per unit mass equals proper energy per unit mass plus pressure times volume per unit mass (reciprocal of mass density).
